        "trailText":"Readers nominate ten must-hear Lou Reed and Velvet Underground tracks for those discovering the man's music for the first time",
        "headline":"Lou Reed: a beginner's guide",
        "body":"<p>The tributes and retrospectives following Lou Reed's death will inevitably lead to many people discovering his music for the first time. But where to start? Some would point to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/nov/05/velvet-underground-nico-readers-review\">The Velvet Underground &amp; Nico</a>, or solo album <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/sep/22/transformer-lou-reed\">Transformer</a>, as possible kicking off points.</p> <p>We asked Guardian readers to help compile a playlist of ten tracks for people who've never listened to Lou Reed of the Velvet Underground before. Here's what they came up with – listen via the <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLjjJcJNDIhap4ZTJxFinJujvECA7SL4d4&amp;feature=mh_lolz\">YouTube playlist</a>, or click the song title to play an individual track:</p> <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLjjJcJNDIhap4ZTJxFinJujvECA7SL4d4&amp;feature=mh_lolz\"> <iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/videoseries?wmode=opaque&amp;list=PLjjJcJNDIhap4ZTJxFinJujvECA7SL4d4\" width=\"460\" height=\"345\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe> </figure> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kwLlvcDi4PQ\">1. Coney Island Baby</a></h2> <p>&quot;It's probably Reed's most poignant reflection on and recollection of his childhood and youth. His spoken-word delivery is marvellous, often slightly behind the beat. You can tell this is a song that meant something special to him. It's there in the mood of the song, the careful and considered instrumentation and more than anything in the lyrics and their delivery.&quot; Mads Kj&aelig;r Larsen</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7d69mDT11yI\">2. Sister Ray</a></h2> <p>&quot;It's almost as if Lou Reed defied the conventions of punk nearly a decade before it even began. The pounding, uncompromising riff the fulcrum for almost twenty minutes around a cacophony of demented organ, Maureen Tucker's relentless rhythm, and the bizarre and rather shocking lyrics. White Light/White Heat is the epitome of New York misanthropy set to wild, courageous sounds and Sister Ray is the jewel of the crown.&quot; Perry Hewitt</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bkG9BKgDvNI\">3. Street Hassle</a></h2> <p>&quot;The cello ... a plaintive human voice caught in an endless loop of pain. And the song is daring beyond anything I'd ever heard. A window into a dark heart.&quot; Emily</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0KaWSOlASWc\">4. Walk on the Wild Side</a></h2> <p>&quot;It was like a subliminal message as a gay male in my early teens … The lyrics suggested there was a language of diversity and rawness, lived out there in the world by real people.&quot; Bernie Harrison</p> <p>&quot;Original, hypnotic, ground-breaking and eye opening.&quot; Katy Rose</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FH2EgYq_NCY\">5. Satellite of Love</a></h2> <p>&quot;Lou's rich vocals coupled with Bowies ethereal chorus. The camp bit in the middle. Evocative memories of my misspent youth.&quot; Colin E</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ffr0opfm6I4\">6. Heroin</a></h2> <p>&quot;The title; the lyrical imagery; the vocal delivery, at once mournful, knowing, amused; the juxtaposition of light and dark, musically and lyrically; the confession and the euphoria; the tempo changes; the quiet/loud dynamic; the fact that so much is wrung out of only TWO chords. He's writen many great, perhaps better, songs, but this is quintessential Reed.&quot; Anon</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NcDuR9BF0Oc\">7. Pale Blue Eyes</a></h2> <p>&quot;A beautiful song which captures Lou Reed's ability to bring melancholy and ever present menace wrapped up in a deceptively soft delivery. Like a love song, that's about to punch you.&quot; Phil</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nkumhBVPGdg\">8. Sweet Jane</a></h2> <p>&quot;One of the greatest riffs ever and some of Lou's best lyrics including an opening to match Jumpin' Jack Flash: 'Standing on the corner / suitcase in my hand / Jack's in his coat and Jane is in her vest / me? I'm in a rock 'n' roll band.' I think there's better stuff on the Velvet's first two albums but they don't really count since Cale's influence was huge. This song, for me, is quintessential Lou Reed, and is up there with the very best rock 'n' roll songs ever recorded.&quot; daldai</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AwzaifhSw2c\">9. Venus in Furs</a></h2> <p>&quot;The S&amp;M subject matter, Cale's wailing violin and Reed's plaintive narration/singing make it so unlike anything that had come before.&quot; Alex McGillivray</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3qK82JvRY5s\">10. Sunday Morning</a></h2> <p>&quot;For me it was the perfect song to encapsulate that morning after period during the second summer of love. Despite the feeling we had come up to the precipice of pure joy and love the night before, now, in the dawn's grey early light, came the restlessness and the feeling that it meant nothing at all – and now we are falling. But oh so sweetly. The song is that musical embodiment of bittersweet chemical comedown when you still feel divine but your heart skips a beat and you don't always quite catch your breath.&quot; Mikey Modface</p> <h2>More</h2> <p>There are a few more tracks to discover on this <a href=\"https://play.spotify.com/user/sjrichards99/playlist/59nnPd72LCwB8q16Hooir0\">Lou Reed Spotify playlist</a>, put together by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2013/oct/26/theguide\">The Guide's</a> music experts:</p> <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-canonical-url=\"https://play.spotify.com/user/sjrichards99/playlist/59nnPd72LCwB8q16Hooir0\" data-alt=\"Lou Reed Spotify playlist\"> <iframe src=\"https://embed.spotify.com/?uri=spotify:user:sjrichards99:playlist:59nnPd72LCwB8q16Hooir0\" width=\"460\" height=\"540\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"></iframe> </figure> <p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/28/lou-reed-career-being-contrary\">Lou Reed: A career of being contrary: </a>The streetwise, tough image was matched by songs of real tenderness and touching fragility. Reed always did the exact opposite of what he was expected to do, writes <strong>Alexis Petridis</strong></p> <p><strong>•</strong> <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/28/neil-gaiman-lou-reed-sandman\">Neil Gaiman on Lou Reed: 'His songs were the soundtrack to my life'</a> Sandman would not have happened without Lou Reed – and I named my daughter after Warhol's Holly Woodlawn, from Walk on the Wild Side. I am sad today, writes <strong>Neil Gaiman </strong></p> <p><strong>• </strong> <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/global/2013/oct/28/lou-reed-everything-strange-exciting-new-york\">Lou Reed held the key to everything strange and exciting in the world:&nbsp;</a>To escape with Lou Reed is to be transported back to 1960s and 70s New York – but also to a place outside of time, writes<strong> <strong><strong>David Shariatmadari</strong></strong></strong></p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/27/lou-reed-velvet-underground-rock-music\">• Lou Reed: the inimitable man rock music was waiting for </a>Reed famously liked his rock and roll simple; he was, when the mood took him, capable of writing perfect pop songs</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421192291|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|2d959b00e029342c0fd5323e020a26150f6c31ca -->",
