      "id":"music/musicblog/2013/oct/31/transformer-lou-reed-sales-surge-death",
      "sectionId":"music",
      "sectionName":"Music",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-31T17:29:27Z",
      "webTitle":"Transformer: Lou Reed's death prompts sales surge",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2013/oct/31/transformer-lou-reed-sales-surge-death",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/musicblog/2013/oct/31/transformer-lou-reed-sales-surge-death",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<strong>Eamonn Forde:</strong> While it is crass to reduce Reed's astonishing influence to downloads, streams and views, renewed interest since his death on Sunday does tell part of the story of what his legacy will be",
        "headline":"Transformer: Lou Reed's death prompts sales surge",
        "body":"<p>\"At the record company meeting, on their hands – at last! – a dead star.\" Morrissey's lyrics in the Smiths' <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1uxP8h0SZRw\" title=\"\">Paint a Vulgar Picture</a> are always brought to mind in the aftermath of a singer dying –  not to mention the apocryphal tale of a nameless music executive who, on hearing of Elvis's passing in 1977, proclaimed it a \"good career move\" with chilling curtness.</p><p></p><p>The death of Lou Reed on Sunday may not be triggering <a href=\"http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/retail/1177325/michael-jackson-two-years-since-his-death-how-much-has-he-sold\" title=\"\">Michael Jackson-style figures</a>, but the late singer <em>is</em> experiencing what chart analysts term a \"significant uptick\" in sales. This would surely have been met with an arched eyebrow by the wonderfully obstinate artist, who was more comfortable in the margins. He only scored two solo hits in the UK during his life – <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qkwD261MHsc\" title=\"\">Walk on the Wild Side</a> reached No 10 in 1973 and a reissue of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FH2EgYq_NCY\" title=\"\">Satellite of Love</a> peaked at the same position in 2004 – although the all-star cover of <a href=\"http://\" title=\"\">Perfect Day</a> for Children in Need rocketed to No 1 in 1997. And while the Velvet Underground might not have sold many copies of their 1967 debut album on its release (anything between 1,000 and 30,000 are cited), \"everyone who bought one of those 30,000 copies started a band\" – as Brian Eno stated in a famous 1982 interview.</p><p></p><p></p><p>Despite Reed's relatively cult status, the music marketing and retail machine has inevitably creaked into gear. Apple's iTunes Store has a \"Remembering Lou Reed\" promotional link on its homepage, which cynics will read as avaricious, even while pragmatists see it as the world's biggest music store simply catering to consumer demand. The demand is clearly there for Lou Reed's music – just not on a multi-platinum level.</p><p></p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.officialcharts.com\" title=\"\">Official Charts Company</a> reports that <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QYEC4TZsy-Y\" title=\"\">Perfect Day</a> has sold 4,700 copies so far this week in the UK (as of Thursday morning) and Walk on the Wild Side has sold 4,000, which means they are both on course to enter the top 40 in Sunday's chart. The next biggest seller is 1973's original <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FH2EgYq_NCY\" title=\"\">Satellite of Love</a> (700 copies), but these sales put it outside the top 100. Reed's 1972 breakthrough album, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/sep/22/transformer-lou-reed\" title=\"\">Transformer</a>, sold fewer than 100 copies last week but has sold around 2,500 copies this week so far, with roughly 80% of sales being digital. It was at No 24 in the album charts on Wednesday but had slipped to 26 this morning. \"The immediate surge of interest has dissipated slightly,\" says Martin Talbot, MD of the Official Charts Company. \"But if it makes top 30 [by the end of the week], that's still quite an achievement in itself.\" Interestingly, there are no Velvet Underground tracks at all in the top 200, so the sales emphasis is almost entirely on Reed's solo work.</p><p></p><p>On Spotify, streams of his music (solo and with the Velvet Underground) were reported by <a href=\"http://www.businessinsider.com/\" title=\"\">Business Insider</a> to have jumped 3,000% following news of his death, and overall it is Transformer that is becoming the default destination for streamers (nine of the 10 most played Lou Reed songs on the service come from it – albeit with Walk on the Wild Side counting twice due to a compilation album inclusion). Tracks from Transformer are equally dominating iTunes downloads and it's the same for online video views, with <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QYEC4TZsy-Y\" title=\"\">Perfect Day</a> (22.4m plays to date), Walk on the Wild Side (6m plays) and Satellite of Love (2.8m plays) proving the most popular songs on YouTube.</p><p></p><p>Looking at the social and online media data tracked by analytics company <a href=\"http://www.musicmetric.com\" title=\"\">Musicmetric</a>, Reed jumped from adding around 1,500 Facebook fans a day this year to adding 37,864 on Monday alone. (Although what newcomers expect from his Facebook page is not clear.)</p><p></p><p>It is crass to reduce Reed's astonishing influence and art to downloads, streams, views and social media \"engagement\" – but they do tell us part of the story of what his posthumous legacy will be. Even those who feel most protective towards his position and his outsider status surely don't wish to deny a whole new audience the opportunity to go down the rabbit hole of his music. Many will naturally stop at the \"greatest hits\" (as the iTunes, Spotify and iTunes figures suggest), but others will burrow deeper and discover for the first time Berlin, White Light/White Heat, Songs for Drella and The Blue Mask – and maybe even <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metal_Machine_Music\" title=\"\">Metal Machine Music</a>.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421397545|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|b9a03dac2fa341325e01fc02e5f48e4259933d99 -->",
